\f1 \cf2 Now I have a clear picture. Here's what I found \'97 the real gaps between what the spec promises and what actually exists, organized by impact on book quality.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The biggest bottleneck isn't the engine. It's the fuel.
\f1\b0 \
Your compiler is solid. The dupe eval, arc alignment, emotional curve validation, overlay substitution \'97 that machinery works. But the content pools feeding it are thin, and several of the spec's most ambitious features exist only on paper. Here's the breakdown:\

\f2\b 1. Atom pool depth is your #1 constraint.
\f1\b0 \'a0You have 68 atom files across 5 personas and ~8 topics, but coverage is wildly uneven. NYC executives have 8 topics. Gen Alpha students and Healthcare RNs have only 2 each. Gen Z professionals \'97 supposedly a core persona \'97 only cover anxiety, depression, and financial stress. That means the compiler\'a0
\f3\i can't
\f1\i0 \'a0produce diverse books for most persona\'d7topic combinations without reusing atoms or hitting pool exhaustion. More atoms per engine (overwhelm, spiral, shame, false_alarm, etc.) and more topic coverage per persona is the single highest-leverage improvement.\

\f2\b 2. Five of the spec's narrative gates don't exist in code.
\f1\b0 \'a0The v4_system_up_spec describes mechanism_escalation_gate, cost_gradient_gate, callback_integrity_gate, identity_shift_gate, and macro_cadence_gate. None of these are implemented. The QA directory has 9 validators, but they cover structural integrity (plan schema, emotional curve, duplication, arc alignment, engine resolution). The\'a0
\f3\i narrative intelligence
\f1\i0 \'a0layer \'97 the thing that would take books from "structurally correct" to "emotionally escalating" \'97 is entirely missing. Those YAML metadata fields (mechanism_depth, cost_type, callback_id, identity_stage, chapter_profile) don't appear on any actual atoms either.\

\f2\b 3. You have 2 arc blueprints for a system that needs dozens.
\f1\b0 \'a0Two master arcs exist (gen_z anxiety/overwhelm F002, and nyc_executives self_worth/shame F006). The wave orchestrator is designed to balance 60 books at a time, but with only 2 arcs the catalog will feel repetitive fast. You need arc blueprints per persona\'d7topic\'d7format combination \'97 or at minimum, a set of reusable arc templates that can be parameterized.\

\f2\b 4. K-tables exist for only 1 format (F006).
\f1\b0 \'a0The spec describes 15 structural formats (F001\'96F015). The format registry has definitions, but only F006 has a K-table (the pool-depth requirement check). Without K-tables for the other formats, the compiler can't validate whether you have enough atoms to fill a given format \'97 it'll either silently degrade or fail at compile time.\

\f2\b 5. Exercises are still stubs.
\f1\b0 \'a0All 11 canonical exercise types exist in the candidate stubs directory, but the approved exercises folder is empty (just a .gitkeep). The system has the overlay substitution engine and validation logic, but no approved exercises to actually slot into books. This means every compiled book would either skip exercise slots or use placeholders.\

\f2\b 6. Teacher bank has a massive candidate
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f2 approved bottleneck.
\f1\b0 \'a0Ahjan (your one teacher) has 190 candidate atoms and 185 approved atoms, which is good \'97 but that's one teacher. The spec envisions a teacher\'d7persona matrix. The approval pipeline exists structurally (candidate 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  approval_logs 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  approved) but there's no automated approval workflow or batch processing tool to accelerate it.\

\f2\b 7. Test coverage is minimal.
\f1\b0 \'a0Two test files: test_emotional_curve_golden.py and test_format_selector.py. The assembly compiler, slot resolver, wave orchestrator, arc loader, all QA validators, the overlay substitution system, naming generator, and freebie renderer have zero test coverage. For a system that stakes its identity on determinism, this is a real risk \'97 you can't guarantee "same inputs 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  same outputs" without regression tests.\

\f2\b 8. No seed mining pipeline exists in code.
\f1\b0 \'a0The spec describes a process for decomposing human-authored source material into atoms (semantic segmentation 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  role mapping 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  rewrite 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  lint 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  repair 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  approval). This pipeline doesn't exist as tooling. Atoms appear to be created manually or semi-manually, which limits throughput.\

\f2\b Where I'd focus, in order:
\f1\b0 \
First, build out the atom pools \'97 especially for underserved personas (healthcare, gen alpha, gen z). More engines per topic, more topics per persona. This directly unlocks more books the compiler can produce without repetition.\
Second, implement the five narrative gates from the spec. Add the metadata fields to the atom schema, tag existing atoms, and write the CI gate code. This is what takes books from "assembled correctly" to "emotionally progressive."\
Third, create more arc blueprints \'97 even 5\'9610 parameterized templates would dramatically increase catalog variety.\
Fourth, approve the exercise stubs and write K-tables for your active formats.\
Fifth, add regression tests for the core pipeline (assembly compiler 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  slot resolver 
\f5 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  validator chain).\
Want me to start building any of these? I could draft the five missing CI gates, create arc blueprint templates, or build a seed mining tool to accelerate atom creation.\
