\f2\b \cf2 What makes an atom great vs. mediocre in this system.
\f1\b0 \
I've read every spec, the writer comms doc, and studied your best existing atoms (the nyc_executives anxiety/false_alarm set is the gold standard \'97 David's email spike, Sarah's rescheduled meeting, Michael's unscheduled partner meeting). Here's what I've internalized about what makes those atoms\'a0
\f3\i work
\f1\i0 :\

\f2\b The atom is a held moment, not a summary.
\f1\b0 \'a0David doesn't "feel anxious about emails." His chest tightens before he opens it. The email is about the holiday schedule. The body prepared for termination. The gap between what the body prepared for and what was actually happening \'97 that's the mechanism made visible without naming it.\

\f2\b Named characters with specific, visible detail.
\f1\b0 \'a0Not "a woman" \'97 Sarah. Not "at work" \'97 the client's assistant calls to reschedule. Not "she felt worried" \'97 her hands go cold before she hears the rest of the sentence. The specificity is what makes TTS work. A flat robot voice reading "her hands go cold" lands. A flat robot voice reading "she felt increasingly anxious about the situation" is dead air.\

\f2\b The engine determines the emotional logic.
\f1\b0 \'a0False_alarm atoms show the gap between alarm and reality. Shame atoms show the moment someone\'a0
\f3\i sees themselves being seen
\f1\i0 . Overwhelm atoms show accumulation past capacity. Spiral atoms show recursive thought loops. Each engine has a distinct mechanism, and the atom must embody that mechanism \'97 not describe it, embody it.\

\f2\b No resolution. The atom ends unresolved.
\f1\b0 \'a0Even EMBODIMENT atoms (the "furthest along" role) don't resolve. David waits sixty seconds before opening the email. The waiting proves he has a choice. But the spike still happened. The system still fired. Coexistence, not recovery.\

\f2\b Third person present tense only for STORY.
\f1\b0 \'a0"David's phone buzzes" not "David's phone buzzed." This is non-negotiable and it's what makes TTS land \'97 present tense puts the listener\'a0
\f3\i in the room
\f1\i0 .\
\

\f2\b My plan for writing at quality across 1,200+ atoms.
\f1\b0 \

\f2\b Step 1: Character bible per persona.
\f1\b0 \'a0Before writing a single atom, I'd build a cast of 8-10 named characters per persona with specific details \'97 job title, physical mannerisms, relationship details, the sensory world they inhabit. NYC executives have glass-walled offices, the 43rd floor, the managing partner. Educators have staff meetings, parent emails, after-school clubs. Healthcare RNs need the ICU, the nurses' station, 12-hour shifts, the beep of monitors. Gen Z professionals need open-plan offices, Slack notifications, standup meetings, imposter syndrome at 24. Gen Alpha students need group chats, the cafeteria, the hallway between classes, parental expectations on a phone screen. These characters recur across engines \'97 David appears in false_alarm AND shame AND spiral \'97 but the engine changes\'a0
\f3\i what the moment reveals about the mechanism
\f1\i0 .\

\f2\b Step 2: Engine-first writing, not topic-first.
\f1\b0 \'a0I'd write all\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 shame
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0atoms across all personas before moving to the next engine. This keeps the engine's emotional logic consistent. Shame is about being seen \'97 the moment of exposure, the heat in the face, the compulsion to hide. If I write shame for educators, then shame for healthcare RNs, then shame for Gen Z, the engine stays sharp. If I write all educator atoms across all engines at once, the engines start bleeding into each other.\

\f2\b Step 3: Band distribution per file.
\f1\b0 \'a0Every 20-atom file needs band variety: roughly 1\'d7 band 1, 4\'d7 band 2, 7\'d7 band 3, 5\'d7 band 4, 3\'d7 band 5. The compiler needs at least 3 distinct bands. I'd tag bands during writing, not after \'97 the band determines how hot the prose runs. A band 1 recognition is mild ("the email notification pings; a brief tightness in the chest, then it passes"). A band 5 recognition is crisis ("the room is spinning; she can't feel her hands; the words on the screen aren't words anymore").\

\f2\b Step 4: Narrative metadata from the start.
\f1\b0 \'a0Since you've now got the\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 _parse_narrative_metadata
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0function reading MECHANISM_DEPTH, COST_TYPE, COST_INTENSITY, IDENTITY_STAGE, CALLBACK_ID, and CALLBACK_PHASE \'97 I'd write atoms with those tags from day one. Early RECOGNITION atoms get mechanism_depth=1, cost_type=social, identity_stage=pre_awareness. Late EMBODIMENT atoms get mechanism_depth=3 or 4, identity_stage=experimentation. This means the narrative gates will have real data to validate against from the start.\

\f2\b Step 5: The four-role escalation arc within each 20-atom set.
\f1\b0 \'a0RECOGNITION (5 atoms): the pattern appears, the person doesn't yet see it. MECHANISM_PROOF (5): the pattern repeats reliably, the system's logic becomes visible. TURNING_POINT (5): new information changes the relationship to the pattern \'97 not fixes it,\'a0
\f3\i changes the relationship to it
\f1\i0 . EMBODIMENT (5): the person acts alongside the pattern, imperfectly, without the pattern dissolving. Each role is a deeper cut. The atoms within a role are\'a0
\f3\i variants
\f1\i0 , not a sequence \'97 atom v01 and v05 of RECOGNITION are parallel options, not chapter 1 and chapter 5.\

\f2\b Step 6: Body anchors are non-negotiable.
\f1\b0 \'a0Every atom gets a concrete physical detail. Not emotions \'97 sensations. Chest tight. Hands cold. Neck hot. Jaw clenched. Stomach dropping. The robot voice can't convey tone, so the\'a0
\f3\i body
\f1\i0 \'a0conveys the emotional weight. I'd keep a running tally: no repeat of the same body anchor within 3 atoms of the same role.\

\f2\b Step 7: Priority order.
\f1\b0 \'a0I'd write the highest-impact gaps first: (a) the 3 nearly-complete personas (close the gaps for educators, nyc_executives \'97 3 files, 60 atoms), then (b) gen_z_professionals anxiety engines (the persona already has HOOK/SCENE/REFLECTION/EXERCISE atoms \'97 adding 6 more engine files gives you a fully compilable persona), then (c) expand healthcare_rns and gen_alpha_students topic by topic.\
