\f2\b \cf2 Tagging alone won't work.
\f1\b0 \'a0The old-style atoms (nyc_executives, most of educators, gen_z anxiety/overwhelm) are fundamentally different prose \'97 40-70 words per block, flat escalation, no callbacks, behavioral shift only. The new-style atoms (healthcare_rns, gen_alpha_students, and the 4 educator files I just wrote) are 140-200 words per block with clear depth escalation, callback architecture, and epistemological identity shift.\
If you just slap MECHANISM_DEPTH: 4 on a 50-word block that reads like a depth-1, the assembly compiler will place it in a late chapter where it doesn't belong. The reader will feel the flatness. The narrative gates might technically pass with the right numbers, but the prose won't deliver what those numbers promise.\
You have two real options. First, rewrite the old atoms to match the new standard \'97 about 63 CANONICAL.txt files need full rewrites (nyc_executives \uc0\u8776  24 files, educators \u8776  17 files, gen_z 1 file). That's the honest fix and it's what makes the books actually good. Second, a hybrid where you tag the old atoms accurately (most blocks at depth 1-2, cost 1-2, pre_awareness) and only use them for early/shallow chapters, then write new deep atoms for the late-chapter slots. But this means you'd need additional atoms per file, which breaks the 20-block-per-file structure.\
Option one is cleaner. It's roughly 42 files to rewrite (the 63 minus the ones that are close enough). Want me to start rewriting them? I'd go persona by persona \'97 nyc_executives first since it's the biggest gap.\
