Use a modular family system:\
1. Core Engine (reusable, 60-70%)\
   * Your universal framework: problem diagnosis, behavior loop, regulation method, action ladder, relapse protocol.\
   * Write once in neutral secular language.\
2. Category Wrapper (15-20%)\
   * Swap framing for each big category (mindset, habits, resilience, etc.).\
   * Add category-specific examples, myths, and research references.\
3. Persona Metadata Layer (5-10%)\
   * Audience-specific context: women leaders, first-gen professionals, caregivers, founders, etc.\
   * Mostly intros/outros, examples, objections, and case stories.\
4. Subtopic Micro-Copy (5-10%)\
* Thin inserts: scripts, checklists, journaling prompts, breathing protocol variants, boundary scripts.\
Writing volume vs traditional prose plan\
Typical \'93full custom book\'94 plan:\
* ~35k-55k words per title from scratch.\
Template-family plan:\
* First family build: ~25k-35k words (heavy lift once).\
* Each new title in that family: ~6k-12k new words.\
* Each micro-variant/subtopic edition: ~2k-5k new words.\
So you can often cut new writing by 60-85% per additional title.\
How this differs from a classic book prose plan\
Classic plan:\
* Book-by-book, linear writing, unique manuscript each time.\
Family-template plan:\
* System-first, component writing, metadata-driven assembly.\
* You write assets, not just books.\
* Output becomes scalable: one core can power audiobook, workbook, short edition, persona edition, and course scripts.\
