1. Catalog Architecture: Standalone Books, Not Funnels\
The Governing Principle\
People search for books, not series. Social media drives discovery. Each book must win its own market. The series is a bonus, not a requirement.\
This means the catalog is\'a0landing-page architecture, not funnel architecture:\
Traditional SeriesPhoenix CatalogBook 1 sells Book 2Social media sells each book independentlySequential reading assumedAny-order reading assumedSeries brand matters mostIndividual book title + persona subtitle matters mostReader buys the setListener finds one book via search/TikTok, may discover othersCliffhangers, "next time" hooksEach book is complete and satisfying\
Implication for the planner:\'a0Every book must be compilable, purchasable, and therapeutically complete without reference to any other book. The series wrapper provides metadata inheritance and catalog organization \'97 not narrative dependency.\
The Four Non-Negotiable Standalone Rules\
Rule 1: No "Previously in This Series" Content.\'a0Each book assumes zero prior reading. The listener found this book through TikTok. They've never heard of the series.\
Rule 2: Each Book Owns a Search Term.\'a0Every book maps to a real query people type into Audible, Google, or TikTok. If a book doesn't own a search term, fold it into another book as a chapter. The consumer_language_map.yaml governs which terms each topic owns.\
Rule 3: Different Valuable Information Per Book.\'a0Same mechanism, different engine. Same persona, different world. Same arc shape, different emotional terrain. The "cocktail party test": a listener should describe two books as obviously different.\
Rule 4: Audible Algorithm Compatibility.\'a0Each book must have: unique title+subtitle, unique ISBN, distinct BISAC subcategory placement where possible, and unique keyword set. No two books from the same brand should compete for identical keywords.\
2. Series Architecture: Three Models Layered\
Model A \'97 Topic Series (The Catalog Spine)\
Each book covers a distinct topic. "Stop Overthinking," "Burnout Recovery," "People Pleasing."\
* Market function:\'a0Each book owns a high-volume keyword\
* Writing cost:\'a0Moderate \'97 each topic needs its own engines\
* Catalog function:\'a0The backbone; every persona variant drafts behind these\
Model B \'97 Progressive Depth (The Curriculum)\
For Tier 1 topics only: Book 1 = Recognition + Foundations. Book 2 = Advanced Tools + Integration.\
* Market function:\'a0Captures "I finished the first one, what's next?"\
* Writing cost:\'a0Low \'97 same topic/engines, different arc emphasis\
* Catalog function:\'a0Doubles Tier 1 titles with minimal new atoms (~30% additional)\
Model C \'97 Persona Variants (The Mirror)\
Same topic, repackaged for different listeners. "Stop Overthinking" becomes "Stop Overthinking: A Recovery Guide for the Overoptimized Mind" (tech workers) vs "Stop Overthinking: Quieting the Noise After the House Goes Silent" (parents).\
* Market function:\'a0HIGH \'97 persona subtitle converts browsers to buyers ("this is for ME")\
* Writing cost:\'a0LOWEST \'97 same mechanisms, same arcs, different templates + variables\
* Catalog function:\'a0Multiplier; each topic \'d7 persona = new standalone title\
