\f1 \cf2 This is a strong, complete spec. Reads like a real production document \'97 not a wishlist. A few observations after reading it fully:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What's very good
\f1\b0 \
The TTS-first framing in \'a71 is the right anchor. Every rule traces back to "robot reads this flat at 150 WPM" which keeps writers from drifting into prose-for-reading habits. The sentence length caps by function type (\'a712.1) are unusually precise and will catch the most common TTS failures.\
The CI governance table in \'a716 is the spec working as it should \'97 machine-enforceable rules with explicit thresholds, not editorial guidelines. That's the difference between a style guide and a production system.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 emotional_intensity_band
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0in \'a74.3 being a hard lint-fail without it set is the right call. It forces writers to consciously assign emotional weight rather than letting the compiler guess.\
The integration modes + reframe types taxonomy in \'a78 is clean. Five modes, five reframe types, one carry line max 8 words. Writers can internalize this.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 What might create friction
\f1\b0 \
The REFLECTION voice spec shifted between sessions. \'a72 says REFLECTION is "First-person author to second-person listener" but the canonical files use pure first-person author voice. The \'a74.4 reflective beat rule ("directs the listener to their own experience, second-person") clarifies the hybrid, but writers will need an explicit example of both modes in the same REFLECTION or they'll drift one way.\
Gate T01 (teaching sentence > 12 words = hard fail) will generate a lot of rewrites until writers internalize it. 12 words is genuinely short for a teaching sentence. Worth adding 3\'964 example rewrites directly in the spec so writers see the transformation in action, not just the rule.\

\f2\b What's not in here yet that we discussed
\f1\b0 \
The chapter archetype system \'97\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 arc_role
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ,\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 exercise_mode
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ,\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 reflection_weight
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 ,\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 story_depth
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 , novelty scorer, transition compatibility rules \'97 none of that is in this spec. \'a722 has "Example Chapter Shapes" which is hand-coded examples, not the archetype-driven system. That's fine if dev is building it separately, but the writer spec will need a \'a722 upgrade once the archetype system exists, otherwise writers won't know how to tag for it.\
The book-level exercise quotas by size (short / mid / full) also aren't here. Once that's coded, it needs to surface to writers so they know the cap before they write, not after CI fails.\

\f2\b One flag
\f1\b0 \
\'a715.1 bans\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 "Nervous system" (> 4x/chapter without fresh context)
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0\'97 but the existing CANONICAL files use "nervous system" as a primary mechanism term, sometimes 4\'966 times in a 300-word reflection. If this gate is CI-enforced against existing atoms, you'll get retroactive failures on content that passed before. Worth confirming whether Gate S01 applies to existing canonical atoms or only new submissions.\
Overall this is ready to hand to writers and dev. The gaps are known and sequenced, not structural problems.\
