\f2\b \cf2 Dropping educators
\f1\b0 \'a0makes sense. The revenue ceiling is low \'97 teachers are time-poor, underpaid, and the profession doesn't cluster in the high-spending demographics. More importantly, the content you'd write for them (classroom management stress, admin pressure, compassion fatigue with students) has a narrow self-help audiobook market. The atoms you've already written for educators aren't wasted \'97 the compassion fatigue, boundaries, and self_worth content translates directly to working parents and healthcare-adjacent personas with minimal reframing. But don't spend more production cycles there.\

\f2\b Keeping gen_alpha with repositioning is smart
\f1\b0 \'a0for three reasons. First, working parents (persona 9 from the market doc) are a $70-100M segment whose #1 topic is communication and relationships \'97 specifically with their children. Gen Alpha content becomes the raw material for a "parenting gen alpha" layer in those books. Second, the intergenerational trauma angle runs in both directions \'97 parents trying to break cycles need to understand who their kids actually are, not just the parent's psychology. Third, gen_alpha content has direct utility for school counselors, family therapists, and youth-facing platforms (YouTube, TikTok, educational apps) if you ever expand beyond audiobooks.\

\f2\b Practically what this means for the system:
